   JURORS CHOSEN in Mapplethorpe obscenity case.
   Prosecutors and defense attorneys in the obscenity and
child nudity case against Cincinnati's Contemporary Arts
Center and its director settled on a jury of four men and
four women, ending four days of jury selection.
   The case is the first ever in the U.S. in which a museum
has been charged with obscenity. The charges center on seven
photographs in an exhibit of 175 works by the late Robert
Mapplethorpe.
   None of the eight jurors or the two alternate jurors
selected had heard of the artist before April or seen his
retrospective exhibit. Only two, a sales associate at a
sporting goods outlet and an export coordinator for Procter &amp;
Gamble, live in the city. The rest, including a warehouse
manager, a data processor, an electrical engineer, a
secretary, hospital quality control specialist and a systems
technician for Cincinnnati Bell Telephone Co. live in the
conservative suburbs. At least four have been active church
members.
   Hamilton County Municipal Judge David H. Albanese has
asked reporters covering the trial not to publish the names
of the jurors because of possible harassment. Defense lawyers
declined to comment on the jury pool.
   Jury selection is considered by many trial lawyers to be
the most important part of a trial, but the makeup of the
jury will have added significance in this case. The law
regarding obscenity hinges on whether the material in
question falls within average and acceptable community
standards or whether it appeals purely to prurient interest
and has no redeeming literary or artistic merit. Jurors in
this case will act as the conscience of their community and
pass judgment on what their community's standards should be.
   Throughout the jury selection, Hamilton County's chief
prosecutor, Frank Prouty, systematically weeded out potential
jurors who indicated an interest in art or in visiting art
galleries and museums.
   None of the jurors has ever been to the Center for
Contemporary Arts, and one hasn't been to an art gallery or
museum since grade school.
   Opening arguments in the case are set to begin this
morning.
   The photos in question -- five depicting homoerotic and
sadomasochistic images and two in which children posed with
their genitals exposed -- caused a furor here when the show
opened in April. The center and its director, Dennis Barrie,
are each charged with one misdemeanor count of pandering and
one misdemeanor count of using a minor in material with
nudity.
