   FORMER S&amp;L EXECUTIVE pleads guilty to federal bank fraud
and tax evasion.
   Donald Moskowitz, former president, chief executive
officer and chairman of United Savings Bank in Paterson,
N.J., admitted in federal court in Newark, N.J., that he used
bank funds to pay for personal expenses, took kickbacks from
loan customers and bank suppliers and evaded more than
$40,000 in personal income taxes. Judge Alfred M. Wolin
accepted his plea.
   Mr. Moskowitz, who faces a maximum of 30 years in prison,
restitution and $1,350,000 in fines, misappropriated $325,000
in bank funds for personal use. He also estimated that the
fraud cost the bank between $2 million to $2.5 million.
   According to Stuart Rabner, an assistant U.S. attorney,
United Savings Bank is one of the nation's top 100
fraud-ridden thrifts. The Resolution Trust Corporation took
over the bank in May.
   "Obviously, his misappropriation of bank funds . . .
jeopardized the bank's funds," Mr. Rabner said. Mr.
Moskowitz's attorney, Edward Fitzpatrick, could not be
reached for comment.
