   JUDGE REFUSES to limit SEC's questioning of German broker.
   The broker, Hans-Jurgen Klisch, is a defendant in the
Securities and Exchange Commission's civil suit alleging
insider-trading in connection with GTE Corp.'s merger with
Contel Corp. The $6.2 billion merger was announced July 12.
Mr. Klisch and others are charged with trading Contel
securities based on inside information about the merger.
   Mr. Klisch, a broker for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Dusseldorf, West Germany, had asked federal Judge Charles
Haight in Manhattan to restrict the scope of the SEC's
questioning. Mr. Klisch said he feared the SEC would ask him
about his brokerage clients, which he said could lead to
violations of German law on disclosing information about bank
customers.
   Judge Haight, however, ruled that because Mr. Klisch would
face civil, rather than criminal, penalties for such
disclosures, the SEC couldn't be restricted.
   The deposition of Mr. Klisch was scheduled for today in
Dusseldorf.
